<p>The previous cells contain just functions. The following script makes the function calls necessary to compile the results for this season and last season into two datasets and a master list of players who played any minutes at all in the premier league last season and their ratings. I exported the outputs from this script into three separate CSV files. Since this script took 15-20 minutes to run because it had to download 570 webpages, I ran it once in full and saved the data. I replaced the actual number of matches played in the two seasons with 1 so you can run the script if you want to. I included comments to make it easy to follow. In the next section, where I actually use all this data, I read it directly from a GitHub link I set up.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[5]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># This code takes between 15-20 minutes to run to run through all the pages.</span>
<span class="c1"># I&#39;ve modified num_matches_2018 and num_matches_2019 appropriately so that doesn&#39;t happen.</span>
<span class="c1"># I ran it once with full number of matches, saved the results, and uploaded them to GitHub.</span>
<span class="c1"># In the next section, I directly read these files from the GitHub links.</span>

<span class="c1">##### Extract Match Info #####</span>

<span class="c1"># there are 380 matches played in a season, there are 20 teams and each team plays every other team twice. </span>
<span class="n">num_matches_2018</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="c1">#380</span>
<span class="n">num_matches_2019</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="c1">#190</span>

<span class="c1"># list of match IDs for the games played last season, I found these by reading through the html on the website</span>
<span class="n">match_ids_2018</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">22342</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">i</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">num_matches_2018</span><span class="p">)]</span>
<span class="n">match_ids_2019</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">38313</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">i</span> <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">num_matches_2019</span><span class="p">)]</span>

<span class="c1"># extract data for each season</span>
<span class="n">data_2018</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">extract_epl_match_details</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">match_ids_2018</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">data_2019</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">extract_epl_match_details</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">match_ids_2019</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># combine data to create a master dictionary</span>
<span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">{</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="n">data_2018</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="o">**</span><span class="n">data_2019</span><span class="p">}</span>

<span class="c1"># convert data from dictionary to dataframe</span>
<span class="n">df_2018</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">convert_to_dataframe</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data_2018</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">match_ids_2018</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df_2019</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">convert_to_dataframe</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data_2019</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">match_ids_2019</span><span class="p">)</span>


<span class="c1">##### Compile Player Names and Ratings #####</span>

<span class="c1"># import master FIFA19 file, includes just fifa ratings </span>
<span class="n">fifa_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kafagy/fifa-FUT-Data/master/FIFA19.csv&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># remove special characters from the name column (accented e&#39;s etc)</span>
<span class="n">fifa_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;NAME&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fifa_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;NAME&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">transform</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">unidecode</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">unidecode</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># add last name column to dataframe to aid querying</span>
<span class="n">fifa_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;LAST_NAME&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fifa_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;NAME&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">transform</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">last_name</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># import missing fifa data, this is the  missing data file I created</span>
<span class="n">missing_fifa_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;https://raw.githubusercontent.com/shahzoor/FIFA_PROJECT/master/missing_player_ratings_final.csv&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># initiaize dictionary to hold player data</span>
<span class="n">name_team_rating_dict</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">dict</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># extract player name, club, and rating for every player who played any minutes at all in the epl in the last two seasons</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="nb">id</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">match_ids_2018</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">match_ids_2019</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="nb">id</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;home_player&quot;</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">)]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">name</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="nb">id</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;home_player&quot;</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">)])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">strip</span><span class="p">()</span>
            <span class="n">club</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">remove_team_code</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="nb">id</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;home_team&quot;</span><span class="p">])</span>
            <span class="n">rating</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">extract_fifa_rating</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">fifa_data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">missing_fifa_data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">name</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">club</span><span class="p">)</span>
            <span class="n">name_team_rating_dict</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">club</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">rating</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">j</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="nb">id</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;away_player&quot;</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">j</span><span class="p">)]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;&#39;</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">name</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="nb">id</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;away_player&quot;</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">j</span><span class="p">)])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">strip</span><span class="p">()</span>
            <span class="n">club</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">remove_team_code</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="nb">id</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;away_team&quot;</span><span class="p">])</span>
            <span class="n">rating</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">extract_fifa_rating</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">fifa_data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">missing_fifa_data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">name</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">club</span><span class="p">)</span>
            <span class="n">name_team_rating_dict</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">club</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">rating</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># convert player data dictionary to dataframe</span>
<span class="n">player_data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">name_team_rating_dict</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span>
<span class="n">player_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;CLUB&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;RATING&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>


<span class="c1">##### Export Data #####</span>

<span class="c1"># export dataframes as csv files</span>
<span class="n">df_2018</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;epl_results_2018&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sep</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;,&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<p>Here is the match data for the 2017/2018 season. I show just the first five results. There were 380 matches played in total over 38 match days. The data from this season is identically formatted but with fewer rows.</p>

<p>Now, back to the analysis.</p>
<p>Let's first briefly analyze these player ratings. The function below will produce a swarm plot with a super imposed boxplot for each club in the league.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[13]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">make_swarmplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">point_size</span> <span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">point_color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;darkgrey&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">box_pal</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;Blues&quot;</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;Make a swarmplot with a boxplot super imposed given a dataset and two variables to focus on. The ylabel</span>
<span class="sd">    must be categorical. </span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame df: Dataframe, must have categorical and numeric data.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param str xlabel: Label of column with numeric data, must match df.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param str ylabel: Label of column with categorical data, must match df.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param axes ax: Axis object from mpl. </span>
<span class="sd">    :param dict box_pal: A custome color palette for the box plots.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: The original axis object with the plot imposed on it.</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: axes</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>

    <span class="c1"># make box plot for each category/club</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">boxplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">whis</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">inf</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">palette</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">box_pal</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">width</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.3</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># make swarm plot for each category/club</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">swarmplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">size</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">point_size</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">point_color</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">alpha</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.85</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># remove the top and right line in graph</span>
    <span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">despine</span><span class="p">()</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># set size</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_size_inches</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># set labels</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">lower</span><span class="p">())</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">capitalize</span><span class="p">())</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_ylabel</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">lower</span><span class="p">())</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">capitalize</span><span class="p">())</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">grid</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">ax</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<p>Conventionally, the "big six" in the Premier League are Arsenal, Liverpool, Chelsea, Manchester City, Manchester United, and Tottenham Hotspur. These six teams consistently finish in the top six positions in the league in some order and have much higher wage budgets than the other teams. This is borne out in the figure below. The boxplots for these six clubs are the ones farthest right indicating higher-rated players.</p>
<p>You might also notice that this graph has 23 teams even though the Premier League has just 20 teams. This is because of the relegation/promotion system in most football leagues (notably excluding the MLS). Since I compiled a master list of players who made appearances in the Premier League both this and last season, it contains data for relegated and promoted players. Stoke City, Swansea City, and West Bromwich Albion were relegated to the second division last year and replaced by Cardiff City, Wolverhampton Wanderers, and Fulham.</p>

<span class="n">ax_players</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplot</span><span class="p">()</span>

</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>How will these ratings help?</p>
<p>I am basically trying to estimate the probability of a match outcome conditional on the difference in average rating between two teams. In (my best attempt at) math:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Let <b>Y</b> ~ the outcome of a game <br></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><b>Y</b> can take values in the set {win, draw, loss}</p><p style="text-align: center;">Let <b>D</b> ~ the absolute difference in rating between two teams <br></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><b>D</b> can take on any real value <b>d</b> in  [0,100]</p><p>I want to estimate $P(Y | D = d)$ <br></p>
<p>So the next thing I do is compute the average rating for both the home and away team for every match played in the 2017/18 season and then take the difference. These differences are appended to the dataframe. The two functions that do this are in the cell below. The function call is in the cell that follows.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[15]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># these functions compute the rating averages for teams, the differences, and append them to the match data dataframes </span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">compute_team_average</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">names</span> <span class="p">,</span><span class="n">ratings</span> <span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;This function computes the average rating for a list of players. It accounts for any empty</span>
<span class="sd">    strings (i.e. &#39;&#39;) in the list.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param: list names : A list of names of the players.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param: DataFrame ratings : An appropriately formatted dataframe containing player ratings.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: The average rating of the players passed in.</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: float</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    
    <span class="c1">#initialize return variable</span>
    <span class="n">average</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>  
    <span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span> 
    
    <span class="c1"># only count players who actually appeared, ignore empty places and NaN values</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">name</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">names</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="nb">type</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">average</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">average</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">ratings</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">ratings</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;NAME&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">strip</span><span class="p">()][</span><span class="s2">&quot;RATING&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">min</span><span class="p">()</span>
            <span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
            
    <span class="c1"># average contains the sum of all player ratings, thus divide</span>
    <span class="n">average</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">average</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">count</span>
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">average</span>


<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">add_averages_to_df</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">match_data</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">ratings</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;This function appends the following three coloumns to the match data dataframe:</span>
<span class="sd">    home_team_rating, away_team_rating, rating_diff. It returns this modified dataframe.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param: DataFrame match_data: This dataframe must contain the lineups for each game in the set.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param: DataFrame ratings: This dataframe must contain player ratings.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: Appends three columns to the match_data dataframe: one for the average rating for the home team,</span>
<span class="sd">            one for the average rating for the away team, and a column for the average difference.</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: DataFrame        </span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>

    <span class="c1"># initialize lists to store the home team average rating, away team average rating, and average team difference</span>
    <span class="n">home_team_rating</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
    <span class="n">away_team_rating</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
    <span class="n">average_rating_diff</span> <span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[]</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># populate the above list by match</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">match_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">home_team_rating</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">compute_team_average</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">list</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">match_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="n">ratings</span><span class="p">))</span>
        <span class="n">away_team_rating</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">compute_team_average</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">list</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">match_data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">34</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="n">ratings</span><span class="p">))</span>
        <span class="n">average_rating_diff</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">home_team_rating</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">away_team_rating</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">])</span>
        
    <span class="c1"># turn the three lists into series</span>
    <span class="n">home_average_series</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Series</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">home_team_rating</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">away_average_series</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Series</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">away_team_rating</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">average_rating_diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Series</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">average_rating_diff</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># append the series as columns into the dataframe</span>
    <span class="n">match_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;home_average_rating&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">home_average_series</span>
    <span class="n">match_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;away_average_rating&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">away_average_series</span>
    <span class="n">match_data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">average_rating_diff</span>
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">match_data</span>
</pre></div>

     </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[16]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># function calls to compute averages, find differences</span>

<p>The graphs below show the distribution of rating differences for both seasons. The difference in rating is calculated is $D = \overline{R_{home}} - \overline{R_{away}}$ where $\overline{R}$ is the average rating. Very high negative and very positive often arise from the same teams playing each other home and away. For example, when Stoke City played Chelsea away, $D=10.65$. In the reverse fixture, $D= -8.02$. That explains the symmetry of the graph.</p>
<p>The graph also shows that the distribution of average differences this season is quite similar to last season's.</p>

</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>I estimate the conditional distribution of outcomes by binning the differences from the 2017/18 season. Then for each bin, I count the number of matches that fall into it, $k$, and then classify each result as a win, draw, or loss for the higher rated team. The probability of an outcome in a given bin is the number of occurances of a specific outcome (win, loss, or draw) divided by $k$. The two functions below carry this out.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[18]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">estimate_conditional_pdf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">count</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;This function estimates the conditional probability of one bin in the conditional pdf.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame data: Data frame that satisfies: lower_bound &lt;= rating_diff &lt;= upper_bound.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param int count: Number or rows in this dataframe.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: Returns the following three floats: p(win), p(draw), p(loss).</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtye float, float, float</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># count the number of wins </span>
    <span class="c1"># home team wins, home team is higher rated OR away team  wins, away team is higher rated</span>
    <span class="n">wins</span> <span class="o">=</span>  <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;result&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span> 
    <span class="n">wins</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">wins</span> <span class="o">+</span>  <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;result&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span>  
    <span class="c1"># count the number of draws</span>
    <span class="n">draws</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;result&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="c1"># ties</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># count the number of losses</span>
    <span class="c1"># home team wins, away team is highe rated OR away team wins, home team is higher rated  </span>
    <span class="n">losses</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;result&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span>  
    <span class="n">losses</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">losses</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;result&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span> 
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">wins</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">draws</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">losses</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">count</span>
    


<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">estimate_full_conditional_pdf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">_max</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">_bins</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;This function estimates full conditional pdf given data, max differences, and the number of bins (_bins).</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame data: The match data dataframe.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param float _max: The maximum rating difference between two teams in any game played and part of the data dataframe parameter.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param int _bins: The number of bins to be used create the conditional distribution.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: Returns a dataframe containing the conditional pdf.</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: DataFrame</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    
    <span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Difference&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;Win&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;Draw&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;Loss&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;Count&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;Min&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;Max&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;Sum&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">_bins</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="n">pdf</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="p">)</span>  
    
    <span class="n">bin_width</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">_max</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">_bins</span>
    <span class="n">lower_bound</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
    <span class="n">upper_bound</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">bin_width</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># creat bins, estimate pdf for each bin in turn</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="c1"># obtain number of rows in bin</span>
        <span class="n">count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="n">upper_bound</span><span class="p">]</span>\
                <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&gt;=</span> <span class="n">lower_bound</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span>
        
        <span class="c1"># deals with zero difference</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="o">==</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">count</span><span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">count</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span>
        
        <span class="c1"># calculate pdf for =&gt; rating difference in [lower_bound, upper_bound]</span>
        <span class="n">p_win</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p_draw</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p_loss</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">estimate_conditional_pdf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="n">upper_bound</span><span class="p">]</span>\
                                                   <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&gt;=</span> <span class="n">lower_bound</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">count</span><span class="p">)</span>
        
        <span class="c1"># update pdf table row</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Difference&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">&quot;(&quot;</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">lower_bound</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s2">&quot;, &quot;</span> <span class="o">+</span><span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">upper_bound</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="s2">&quot;]&quot;</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Win&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p_win</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Draw&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p_draw</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Loss&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p_loss</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Count&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">count</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Min&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lower_bound</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Max&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">upper_bound</span>
        <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">&quot;Sum&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p_win</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">p_draw</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">p_loss</span>
        
        <span class="c1"># update bounds</span>
        <span class="n">lower_bound</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lower_bound</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">bin_width</span>
        <span class="n">upper_bound</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">upper_bound</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">bin_width</span>
        
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">pdf</span>
            
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>The parameter I have the most control over when trying to estimate the conditional pdf is the number of intervals and, consequently, the interval width. This determines how accurate the estimate is going to be. Since I have just 380 data points in my training set, having very small intervals could result in a lot of empty bins. Having intervals that are too large would miss the point entirely and offer no precision at all. Since the relationship between interval size and accuracy is arguably nonmonotonic, I will estimate several conditional pdfs and then pick out whichever one predicts the most match outcomes correctly for this season.</p>
<p>The next cell finds 22 conditional pdfs. The minimum interval width I set is 0.5 and the maximum interval widths is 11. This is somewhat arbitrary but having smaller widths would result in empty intervals.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">

<span class="n">pdf</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">num</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">math</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ceil</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">_max</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">estimate_full_conditional_pdf</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">rating_games_2018</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">math</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ceil</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">_max</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="n">num</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>

guessing, i.e. guessing $p($win$) = p($draw$) = p($loss$)=1/3$. This is shown below.</p>

<p>The next step is to test these pdfs in turn. I use the data from this season to do that. This testing dataset has 190 points. I know what the lineups are for these games so I can compute the difference in average rating for each of them.</p>
<p>The two functions below use the pdf function and the difference in rating to simulate a set of games. So they will basically draw from a uniform distribution and compare the draw to the pdf function to determine an outcome.</p>
<p>Since I know what the result for each game is, each pdf gets a score based on how many results it guesses correctly.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs  ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[22]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># extract appropriate probabiilities for a single game</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">simulate_single_game</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;Simulates a single game based on the conditional pdf of matching outcomes on rating differences.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame data: The dataframe row of relevent game.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame pdf: The dataframe containing the conditional pdf.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: Returns 1 for a home win, -1 for an away win, and zero for a draw.</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: int</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    
    <span class="n">difference</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">u</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># extract appropriate probabiilities for the game based on the difference</span>
    <span class="c1"># i.e. pick out the relevant row of the full pdf</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">difference</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&gt;=</span><span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Min&quot;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="ow">and</span> <span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">difference</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Max&quot;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]:</span>
            <span class="n">p_win</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p_draw</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">p_loss</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Win&quot;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Draw&quot;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Loss&quot;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span>

    <span class="c1"># determine simulated result based on u (a random draw from unif(0,1))</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">u</span> <span class="o">&lt;=</span> <span class="n">p_win</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">difference</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mi">0</span> <span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
        <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span>
    <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="n">p_win</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="n">u</span> <span class="o">&lt;=</span> <span class="n">p_win</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">p_draw</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
    <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">difference</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span>
        <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>

    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">result</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">simulate_games</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot; Simulates all games by making calls to simulate_single_game based on the conditional pdf of matching outcomes on rating differences.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame data: The dataframe row of relevent game.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame pdf: The dataframe containing the conditional pdf.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: Adds a column to the data dataframe that contains the simulated result.</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: DataFrame</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    
    <span class="n">return_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()</span>

    <span class="c1"># set seed, 42 because of the hitch-hikers guide to the galaxy</span>
    <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">seed</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">42</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="c1"># generate ranndom numbers to help simulate each match</span>
    <span class="n">num_matches</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">return_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">U</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">uniform</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">num_matches</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="c1"># add random numbers to dataframe</span>
    <span class="n">return_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;U&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Series</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">U</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="c1"># simulate all the games</span>
    <span class="n">return_df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;simulated_result&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">return_df</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s2">&quot;rating_diff&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;U&quot;</span><span class="p">]]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">func</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">simulate_single_game</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># remove the U column</span>
    <span class="n">return_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">return_df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">drop</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;U&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">axis</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">return_df</span>

<span class="c1"># checks how many times the simulated result equalled the actual result</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">score_simulation</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot; This function scores the simulation results. It does this by comparinng the simuulated result to the actual results. The score is equal to the </span>
<span class="sd">    number of matches correctly predicted by the simulation.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param DataFrame data: A dataframe containing match data and the simulated results for every game.</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: The score for the simulation. This is equal to the number of times the simulated result equals the actual/observed results.</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: int</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;result&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">==</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;simulated_result&quot;</span><span class="p">]]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

     </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>

    <span class="c1"># create color map</span>

    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">gca</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">grid</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>

<p>The graph above shows the scores for the pdf against the number of bins and bin width. Like I suspected, the relationship between those two factors and the score is not monotonic. The maximum score occurs at $n_{bins}$=$[16, 17, 19]$. Unsurprisingly, the worst score corresponds to zero bins where we do no conditioning at all. All the scores are higher than the purely random score which is $72$.</p>
<p>The graph below show the same graph for the training dataset.</p>

</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">

<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">scores_train</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">)):</span>
    <span class="n">scores_train</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">score_simulation</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">simulate_games</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">match_data_2018</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">])))</span>

<p>The graph below plots all the PDFs against the difference in player ratings. The three estimates that got the highest scores after the simulation are in bold while all the other estimates are lightly visible in the background.</p>

<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">

<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">format_pdf_for_plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">pdfs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">outcome</span> <span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;This function creates a dataframe that has rows that correspond to the probability of an outcome</span>
<span class="sd">    vs the difference in average rating.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    :param list pdfs: A list containing all the pdf estimates. Every element in the list is a dataframe.</span>
<span class="sd">    :param str outcome: The outcome to focus on: &quot;Win&quot;, &quot;Draw&quot;, &quot;Loss&quot;</span>
<span class="sd">    :return: Probability of outcome vs difference for every pdf, each row corresponds to pdf</span>
<span class="sd">    :rtype: DataFrame</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    &quot;&quot;&quot;</span>

    <span class="n">out_list</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
    
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">pdf</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">pdfs</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">q</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">linspace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">pdfs</span><span class="p">))</span>
        <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">q</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">math</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">floor</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Min&quot;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">):</span><span class="n">math</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ceil</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;Max&quot;</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]</span>  <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pdf</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">outcome</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span>
        <span class="n">out_list</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">q</span><span class="p">)</span>
        
    <span class="n">out_df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">out_list</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">out_df</span>
</pre></div>
